709 // We are looking for loops that do something like this:
710 //   int r = 0;
711 //   for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
712 //     if (src[i] > 3)
713 //       r = 3;
714 //   }
715 // where the reduction value (r) only has two states, in this example 0 or 3.
716 // The generated LLVM IR for this type of loop will be like this:
717 //   for.body:
718 //     %r = phi i32 [ %spec.select, %for.body ], [ 0, %entry ]
719 //     ...
720 //     %cmp = icmp sgt i32 %5, 3
721 //     %spec.select = select i1 %cmp, i32 3, i32 %r
722 //     ...
723 // In general we can support vectorization of loops where 'r' flips between
724 // any two non-constants, provided they are loop invariant. The only thing
725 // we actually care about at the end of the loop is whether or not any lane
726 // in the selected vector is different from the start value. The final
727 // across-vector reduction after the loop simply involves choosing the start
728 // value if nothing changed (0 in the example above) or the other selected
729 // value (3 in the example above).
